Isaac Wright on ‘Eunice’ was shot on top of the historical Chrysler Building on a cold winter's day in 2022.

I won’t go too deep into the specifics of how we found ourselves up here, but let’s just say it involved some serious research and some sketchy free climbing. From south to north on the west side of the building, the eagles are named; Phoebe, Marge, Nelly and Maude. From south to north on the east side; Doris, Gladys, June and of course, Eunice which is the eagle that Isaac is standing on.

I have been staring at these eagles my entire life with this frame stuck in my mind, constantly wondering how to make it happen. With all the exploration and time spent climbing buildings all throughout the world over the last twelve years or so, I must say, sitting up here and having a smoke was truly a day I will never forget. Some tears fell as I realized where I was with peers I admire, E and Isaac, what a beautiful space to share. We were surrounded by corporate offices that do not usually see people on this balcony, so I knew we had to be quick. I took it all in while I had the time to do so, I knew exactly where I was, my breathing was calm and hands were steady.

Massive thank you to @em.1t for helping to make this mission successful. I’d also like to thank @mosesgates for doing what he does, we all appreciate you Moses, thank you. 

So much damn noise down there, so much silence up here. #newyorkcity
Make sure you’re able to catch your breath, this town runs on angst. #newyorkcity

What do I even say about these frames? I could have cut corners, I could have produced the books in China and saved a ton of cash. I found Ufuk through a peer of mine and knew this was the way. I hopped on a zoom call with him, he lit a cigarette and he said “book a flight, come stay with me and watch your books get made, you seem very curious.”

So I called Alex. He was down of course, and off we went. Two weeks after that zoom call we were in Istanbul. We arrived at midnight and stayed up till 5am choosing papers. We knew we were in the right space. Surrounded by some of my favorite photo based literature, it was only obvious that this investment was the correct one. Offset lithographic printing is a rare process these days and holy shit was I eager to learn more. 

This book is not just a photobook. A photographic diary is what I’ve chosen to call it, referencing writings and drawings from my abuse ridden childhood. So much pain, but also so much fucking hope? I know one thing, my life’s work is to tell other survivors stories, starting with my own. Childhood sexual victimization is quite an overlooked issue. Photographs have such a unique power to help shape narratives. More on this point soon. 

I’m on quite a journey my friends, stay tuned. I appreciate all of you, some of the messages I’ve been receiving — shit, I have too much to say, per usual haha. I’m honored to open up my brain to those who choose to purchase this diary, I hope I make all of you proud. I know I am damn proud of myself. 

Here are ten frames from long nights spent producing this book in person, a trip that changed my life.

Searching and searching, it has been years now. This is my space, my meditation, my time, my stillness! 

An arduous journey, filled with endless 3am sunrise missions, long nights in subway tunnels and overnight camping trips to the balconies of iconic skyscrapers all over the world. The mission to find a perfect route up these mountains made of steel and glass is one that I'll never tire of.

I’m turning 30 soon, what a thought. I find myself reflecting on my past a lot these days. Here, right fucking here, amidst the clouds, I feel a sense of comfort and security that has been such a monumental part of life for the last thirteen years, as a human and as a photographer. 

This is where I belong, where I feel most at home. Away from the chaos and distractions of the world below, I can breathe just a bit easier up here. I am grateful to share these spaces with a small community of like-minded individuals who share my love of adventure and the never-ending quest for unique perspectives.

Up here, in my own little corner of the sky, there is nothing but breathing room. Yeah, that’s what it’s called, breathing room.
